<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Renewed worries on inflation reversed an initial recovery in Footsie
futures, with a further retreat brought on by continuing weakness of the US
dollar and a fall in US markets, writes Joel Kibazo.
The strong momentum seen on Wednesday looked set to continue after the
September contract on the FT-SE 100 opened at 2,962. Buying, mainly from
independent (local) traders sent September climbing to 2,972 within the
first hour of trading, which turned out to be the high of the day.
A report suggesting UK inflation is higher than had been anticipated,
together with a sharp retreat in gilts, checked a further advance in the
contract. With continuing worries on the US dollar, September went into
decline.
The afternoon only brought further selling as dealers focused on continuing
falls in both US and UK bonds and the decline of Wall Street. At the close,
September stood at 2,919, down 40 from its previous session and about 10
points below its estimated fair value premium of about 13. Volume was 15,211
lots.
Turnover in traded options improved from Wednesday's poor level, reaching
29,220 by the close. Activity in the FT-SE 100 option at 9,286 remained
poor, but there was an improvement in the Euro FT-SE option with a total of
5,924 trades. BP was the busiest stock option at 1,605.
</TEXT>
