<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Weak bonds push Dow sharply
lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks suffered a sharp setback yesterday as nervous investors watched
long-term bond yields push higher, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 42.09 down at 3,624.96, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 fell 3.36 to 444.27. The secondary
markets showed more resilience, with the American SE composite edging
forward 0.60 to 424.08 and the Nasdaq composite firming 1.95 to 705.96.
The morning brought a barrage of fresh economic indicators, none of which
had any direct bearing on the outlook for corporate earnings. Nevertheless,
stocks were derailed by the bond market's bearish reaction to the data.
In particular, fixed-rate investors were put off by a jump in the prices
paid by Chicago-area manufacturers last month. The Purchasing Management
Association of Chicago said its May prices-paid index climbed to 69.7 per
cent, against 63.7 per cent the previous month.
The data was a red flag for the inflation-sensitive government securities
market. In response, the yield on the benchmark 30-year security moved over
the pivotal 7.60 per cent level, sending a shiver through the stock market.
After a positive opening, share prices retreated steadily throughout the
session, which brought the second quarter to a close. Some 293m shares were
exchanged on the Big Board, even though the approach of the long
Independence Day weekend had thinned the ranks on Wall Street.
There were also many investors who preferred to stay on the sidelines
pending the outcome of next week's meeting of the Federal Reserve's policy-
setting arm. The dollar's plight remained an unpleasant sideshow, further
encouraging restraint.
However, two headline acquisition stories provided the session with a touch
of spice. CBS surged ahead Dollars 47, or 17.9 per cent, to Dollars 310 on
news that the media group was in the final stages of negotiating a merger
agreement with QVC. Shares in the home-shopping network jumped Dollars 5 5/8
to Dollars 38. Trading in both issues had been halted until mid-afternoon.
The second deal involved the more staid railway sector, in which mergers
have been rare in recent years. Burlington Northern dipped Dollars  1/8 to
Dollars 53 3/8 and Santa Fe Pacific appreciated Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 20
7/8 after agreeing to combine their operations. The move was anticipated.
Caterpillar continued to feel the effect of a week long strike. The issue
led the Dow indust-rials in decline, dropping Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 100.
After an early gain, UAL, parent of United Airlines, retreated to end a net
Dollars 1 1/8 off at Dollars 126 1/4 . The company modified terms of a plan
which would result in an employee buy-out of the carrier if approved by
shareholders.
Health maintenance organisations were marked down in activity which followed
the approval of a health care reform proposal by the House ways and means
committee. United Healthcare dropped Dollars 2 to Dollars 45 7/8 and US
Healthcare Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 37 amid fears of a federal move to
control the cost of insurance premiums.
Canada
After staging a further improvement, the Toronto market slipped back.
leaving the TSE 300 index ending a net 2.9 points off at 4,025.2.
Advances still led declines, however, by 466 to 309 after moderate volume of
59.5m shares valued at CDollars 638m. On the shortened week, the composite
index has gained about 65 points. Canadian markets are closed today for the
Canada Day holiday.
Brazil
Equities closed 5.36 per cent down in local currency terms after
profit-taking and speculation that the government might take measures that
were expected to keep foreigners out of the market. The Bovespa index lost
2,052 at 36,232 in volume of Cr476.2bn (Dollars 173.1m.
Brokers said there was speculation that the government may increase taxes on
incoming capital and maintain a high spread between bid and ask prices on
certain dollar exchange rates.
But a trader said he did not think the government would lift taxes on
incoming capital because it would hurt the market and the share prices of
blue chip state companies.
Traders added that investors were also taking advantage of the market's rise
over the last three sessions to take profits ahead of today's introduction
of the real.
Inflation in Brazil was 45.2 per cent in June, a rise of 2.63 per cent from
May, agencies report from Rio de Janeiro.
</TEXT>
