<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Heavy offerings in the final week of the 1993/94 selling season in Australia
made little difference to price levels. The market indicator finished at 624
cents a kg., only 3 cents down on the week. Competition at auctions was
good, with China prominent, which is always seen as a strengthening factor.
The season also ended in New Zealand with prices firm. The British wool
selling season opened this week and firmer prices were correctly anticipated
by the trade, though increases only amounted to one or two per cent and are
not universal. Holidays are already an important factor keeping trade quit
and their influence will increase and persist for the next two months. The
UK wool-processing industry is busy but would be a lot happier if higher
wool prices were accepted and passed on by retailers who continue to resist
them.
