<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / International Company News: GE Capital pays Dollars 400m for
Harcourt businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, STAMFORD, CONNECTICUT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
One week after withdrawing its Dollars 2.2bn bid for US insurance and fund
management group Kemper, GE Capital announced it is to pay Dollars 400m cash
for the insurance business of Harcourt General.
The financial services arm of General Electric will acquire three life
insurance companies owned by Harcourt which between them have assets of
Dollars 3bn and generated revenues in the year to last October of Dollars
550m.
The proceeds of the sale, which amount to Dollars 375m after tax, will boost
Harcourt's war chest for future takeovers. Mr Robert Tarr, chief executive,
said the company now had cash balances of Dollars 800m and 'continued to
look for acquisition opportunities'.
Harcourt announced in February that it was planning to sell the companies in
order to concentrate on its publishing and specialty retailing businesses.
It had acquired the three - Federal Home Life, PHF Life and Harvest Life -
as part of the acquisition of the publisher Harcourt Brace Jovanovich in
1991.
GE Capital said it would operate the companies as part of GNA, its existing
insurance business. The companies underwrite individual life, health,
accident and credit insurance, and sell annuity products.
GE Capital dropped its bid for Kemper last week after its offer was topped
by Conseco, another insurance group.
GE Capital and GTE said the GTE Spacenet satellite communications business
would be acquired by GE American Communications, a GE Capital company,
Reuter adds from Stamford, Connecticut. Terms of the deal were not
disclosed.
</TEXT>
