<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / International Company News: Bosch slips to record operating
loss - Two leading forces in Europe's motor industry are struggling to
regain ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Robert Bosch, the privately- owned German electronic and vehicle parts
manufacturer, made an operating loss of more than DM100m (Dollars 61.3m)
last year, the first time it has gone into the red since the second world
war.
The group refused to give any details of the loss, saying only that it ran
into 'high three figures'.
The loss reflected the combination of recession, pressure on prices from the
car manufacturers which are Bosch's biggest customers, low capacity
utilisation, the strength of the D-Mark and the costs of introducing
swingeing rationalisation measures, Mr Hermann Scholl, the group's chairman
said at a press conference in Stuttgart.
There had been an improvement in the general economic climate during the
current year to date, Mr Scholl said, with turnover up just 6 per cent to
DM13.7bn in the first five months of 1994. This was mainly due to a pick-up
in demand outside Germany, and the chairman predicted that sales for the
current year would rise by 4 per cent and that there would be modest
turnover growth in 1995.
But in spite of the improvement in the economy and extensive rationalisation
measures, Bosch would make an operating loss again this year, the chairman
warned.
The cluster of negative factors last year led to a 5.7 per cent drop in
sales to DM32.5bn after DM34.4bn in 1992, the first fall in the group's
turnover since 1967. Pre-tax profits dropped by 63 per cent, from DM1.36bn
to DM510m, while net after-tax earnings fell 17 per cent from DM512m to
DM426m.
While economic conditions had improved since last year, the chairman warned
that price pressures would not diminish and that measures to cut costs and
improve productivity would have to continue. In 1993, 13,200 jobs were cut,
and the plan is to reduce the payroll by a further 4,100 this year, bringing
the total down to 152,500 by the year-end.
Bosch said that it would be restructuring its communications technology
activities: public communications technology, private communications
technology and radio technology are to be brought together into one division
as of July 1.
The division, which generated turnover of DM5.5bn last year, will be divided
into 12 product areas while the businesses will pool their research and
development, marketing and other resources.
The new structure is designed to strengthen Bosch's position in a growing
but intensely competitive market, Mr Scholl said.
</TEXT>
