<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / UK Company News: US input helps raise Ivory &amp; Sime to Pounds
6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ivory &amp; Sime, the Edinburgh-based fund managers, lifted pre-tax profits by
27 per cent, from Pounds 4.9m to Pounds 6.2m, during the year to April 30.
Mr Allan Munro, managing director, said the company was continuing the
progress made in the four years since management changed in 1990. Managed
funds increased by 15 per cent to Pounds 3.8bn at the year end, though the
rise was 'not as fast we would like'.
During the year the company lost the contract to manage portfolios
controlled by the Merchant Navy Officers Pension Fund, leading to Ensign
Trust selling its 16.7 per cent stake to investors including Abtrust and
Scottish Value Trust. I&amp;S also lost the contract to manage New Frontiers
Development fund.
However, funds under management in North America doubled to Pounds 470m
despite the loss of one client worth Pounds 110m. Mr Munro said I&amp;S could
present a good five-year record in managing UK pension funds which meant it
attended 'beauty parades' to win new mandates.
Profits were boosted by the high level of world stock markets over the year.
Sales rose 23 per cent to Pounds 17.6m (Pounds 14.3m).
Administrative expenses rose by 11 per cent to Pounds 11m.
The final dividend is 5.25p, making a total of 7.5p, up 15.4 per cent, and
payable from earnings up 20 per cent to 12.87p per share.
</TEXT>
