<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / BPB profits rise 87% after price war ends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pre-tax profits of BPB Industries, Europe's biggest plasterboard
manufacturer, rose 87 per cent to Pounds 107.7m during the year to March as
the company continued to recover following the end of a 'destructive price
war'.
The profits increase announced yesterday was higher than expected and BPB's
shares rose 4 1/2 per cent to 302p. The price war, which concluded in 1992,
was waged between the UK group, which controls about 50 per cent of the west
European market, and Lafarge Coppee of France and Knauf of Germany, which
split the remainder roughly equally.
BPB said the price of plasterboard in Germany, France and the UK had risen
on average by about a quarter since March 1992 but was still about 25 per
cent lower than at the beginning of 1990.
A 27 per cent fall in manufacturing costs since 1990, however, meant that
prices did not need to reach previous peaks for margins to recover. Margins
on plasterboard and plaster sales last year improved from 8.6 per cent to
12.3 per cent, while sales volume increased by just 4.5 per cent.
Mr Alan Turner, chairman, said that prices might rise by 2 or 3 per cent
this year, but future growth was more likely to be generated by increased
sales rather than price rises. He said the three manufacturers had finally
seen commonsense and ended a price war estimated to have cost the industry
Pounds 200m in lost revenue since 1989.
Prospects now looked bright with European construction activity forecast to
recover over the next two years, led by housebuilding and sharp growth in
eastern Germany where BPB plans to build a large new plant in Berlin costing
almost Pounds 50m. The company also predicted that European sales would rise
as plasterboard continued to increase its market share against other
products.
BPB's advance in pre-tax profits was achieved in spite of a Pounds 3.9m
increase in redundancy and reorganisation costs to Pounds 15.2m.
Turnover grew 2.3 per cent from Pounds 1.12bn to Pounds 1.15bn. Earnings per
share rose by 85 per cent to 15p (8.1p), and a final dividend of 5.3p (4.8p)
makes a total of 8.1p for the year, up 8 per cent on the previous year's
7.5p.
All of the company's main building materials businesses, other than plaster
in Spain and Italy, recorded strong profits growth, while Canada had moved
from break-even to profit.
Lower costs, better prices and higher sales volume had prompted a net cash
inflow of Pounds 95m, helped by a low tax payment of Pounds 2m, a reduced
interest charge of Pounds 18m (Pounds 29.6m) and 'a minimal acquisition
spend'.
Net borrowings fell by Pounds 104.2m to Pounds 138.2m, reducing gearing from
35 per cent to 19 per cent.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
