<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Prudential leads bidders for National Car Parks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, SIMON DAVIES and PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A consortium of venture capital investors, led by UK insurance giant
Prudential, is understood to be behind the bid for National Parking
Corporation, which owns National Car Parks and the fast-growing National
Breakdown Recovery service.
It is believed that the bidding consortium also includes Electra, the
unquoted companies investment trust, CinVen, the venture capital arm of
British Coal's in-house funds manager, and Morgan Grenfell Development
Capital, part of Morgan Grenfell - NPC's financial adviser.
Morgan Grenfell has been sounding out potential buyers for several months
for the 64 per cent of NPC owned by founder Sir Donald Gosling, 65, and Mr
Ronald Hobson, 73, after flotation was ruled out.
The shares, which stood at 450p at the start of the week, rose further to
575p yesterday in over-the-counter trading, valuing the private company at
Pounds 675m. The group made pre-tax profits of Pounds 53.3m on Pounds 233.5m
turnover in the year to March 26, 1993.
Aside from its enormous cash flow, NPC's major attraction would be its
freehold and long-leasehold interests in around 600 car parks, and a number
of property investments.
The properties used by its operating businesses are all valued at cost,
despite the fact that many of the car parks were purchased during the 1950s
and 1960s and are situated in prime locations.
Collins Stewart, the stockbroking firm, estimates that assuming valuations
based on an 11 per cent yield on its car parks, NPC is sitting on a Pounds
200m surplus to its balance sheet property valuation of Pounds 197m. There
is potential for redeveloping prime sites, although in many cases the local
authorities may not be prepared to change the land usage.
The company dominates the provision of private car parking spaces in the UK,
with no sizeable competitors after its 1990 acquisition of rival Europarks.
A near-monopoly has prevailed because of a quirk in the law: car park owners
are not considered to be providing a service and are therefore outside the
auspices of the Office of Fair Trading.
NPC has utilised the cash flow from car parking to build up its highly
successful vehicle breakdown operation, which made Pounds 9.8m profit last
year. Its phone and computer network is now supporting a push into urgent
domestic repair services.
</TEXT>
