<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / CrossRail plan doomed despite MPs' support: Commons
committee remains opposed to route
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The private bill authorising the Pounds 2bn CrossRail plan for an east-west
London railway link is dead, despite an attempt by hundreds of MPs of all
parties to revive it.
More than 250 MPs have signed a Commons motion tabled by Mr David Lidington,
Conservative MP for Aylesbury, calling for a private bill authorising
CrossRail to be sent back to a quasi-judicial committee which rejected it
last month.
The move is backed by Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, and Mr Frank
Dobson, Labour's transport spokesman, as well as the bill's joint sponsors -
British Rail, London Underground and Railtrack, the rail infrastructure
company.
But two of the four MPs on the committee say they will continue to oppose
the scheme, which would authorise a six-mile tunnel linking Paddington and
Liverpool Street main line stations. A third is also thought likely to
oppose.
The MPs' stand means that under parliament's procedures for private
legislation the bill has no hope of success, even if the Commons votes for
Mr Lidington's motion.
It is understood that two of the three committee members who voted against
the project would change their minds if it was amended to link up with the
proposed Heathrow Express and the planned high-speed line from London to the
Channel tunnel.
However, that would require a government commitment to provide up to Pounds
100m in extra public finance, which would be unlikely to be approved by the
Treasury.
The project only reached the committee stage because Mr John Major, the
prime minister, over-ruled attempts by Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary
to the treasury, to block it on cost.
Mr John Marek, one of two Labour MPs on the committee, wrote to all Labour
MPs yesterday insisting that the economic case for the project 'simply did
not stack up'.
In a 13-point critique of the scheme, Mr Marek said that the funds required
to build CrossRail would produce up to 20 times more benefit if spent on the
existing Underground system.
He said the project would duplicate the Central Line, and could cost BR up
to Pounds 100m a year in lost revenue.
The government has ruled out the alternative options of taking over the
project under the 'hybrid' bill procedure - which involves both public and
private interests - or using the 1992 Transport and Works Act.
The DoT is already committed to one hybrid bill for the high-speed rail
link, and is unlikely to be awarded parliamentary time for a second.
Under the Transport and Works Act, Mr MacGregor could simply lay an order
before parliament. But public inquiries could delay the project for at least
10 years.
</TEXT>
