<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Having been scraped off the highway (again) only last week by paramedics
from the ambulance service, I will not have a word said against these
splendid people. But do we really need another ambulance-chasing series? I
would have been less than keen to have a film crew record my every groan as
we charged into casualty, yet that is precisely what Paramedics sets out to
do (8.30 BBC1). Broadcasting bosses would sooner drink Sauternes with their
salmon than countenance a series called 'Women Behaving Badly', but in this
age of rampant feminism it is OK to have a series poking fun at men and
called Men Behaving Badly. To be fair, men do have the toughness and
emotional stability to let such stuff wash over them whereas women, poor
frail things, need the broadcasters' protection (9.30 BBC1). Does ITV's new
chat show, Tarbuck Late, hosted by comedian Jimmy Tarbuck, have any chance
of taking viewers from C4's new series of the improvisation contest Whose
Line Is It Anyway? (both 10.30). In tribute to the late Rudolph Cartier BBC2
shows his Nineteen Eighty Four (11.15).
