<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Managers say strong manufacturing rise hitting supplies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The manufacturing sector is growing strongly, but at the cost of creating
some supply bottlenecks and price pressures, according to figures published
by the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply yesterday.
The purchasing managers' index rose to 61.4 per cent in June, the highest
level since the figures were first published in 1991. The institute
constructs the index from components including new orders and employment. A
figure above 50 per cent indicates that activity has grown since the
previous month, one below 50 per cent indicates a fall.
The index was last below 50 per cent in December 1993, since when it has
risen steadily.
New orders and employment both reached record levels on the month. Order
books improved across all industries and regions, and for domestic and
export markets. Employment was particularly strong in the electrical and
electronic industries, but was described by companies as 'temporary' or
'seasonal'. Output was particularly strong in Wales, the south-east and the
Midlands.
Mr Mark Reckless, UK economist at Warburg Securities, warned that the
index's short history meant that record levels might not be greatly
significant.
The institute also said that raw materials shortages, particularly in pulp
and paper, had raised prices. Its prices index rose from 57.8 per cent in
May to 59.1 per cent in June.
Furthermore, bottlenecks are appearing in the system, indicating further
potential price pressure. Delivery times have been lengthened by suppliers'
inability to meet demand requirements. The institute said that unanticipated
strong demand led to a fall in stock levels in June.
Mr Don Smith, UK economist at Midland Global Markets, said the prices data
'will worry some people because it resonates with the recent CBI survey'
which showed a jump in the number of companies planning to raise prices.
However, Mr Smith said: 'What we see in the institute survey is the
consequence of higher world commodity prices. It doesn't necessarily mean it
will feed through to retail prices.'
The institute compiles its data by interviewing a panel of managers from 300
manufacturing companies.
The UK economy will grow at 3 per cent this year and at 2.6 per cent in
1995, says National Westminster Bank. It predicts underlying inflation will
rise to 3.5 per cent in the fourth quarter of 1995, near the top of the
government's 1 per cent to 4 per cent target range and well above the
Treasury's forecast of 2.75 per cent.
</TEXT>
