<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Treasury grants British Library extra cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Treasury is to put up extra money for the new British Library building
in central London in the expectation that the cash will be recovered from
contractors.
Mr Peter Brooke, heritage secretary, told the Commons national heritage
committee yesterday that the Treasury held the contractors responsible for
delays and cost overruns.
He said the cost of the library would exceed the Pounds 450m ceiling imposed
in 1990, at least in the short term.
The Treasury had agreed to fund the extra spending, having been convinced
that the extra money could be recovered from contractors, whose mistakes in
planning and installing equipment contributed to the spiralling cost of the
project.
Laing Management is the main contractor, but there are dozens of
sub-contractors.
Mr Brooke said he was confident that, after recoveries, the cost would not
exceed Pounds 450m. The alternative was for the British Library to be asked
to take possession of a building lacking some of its planned features.
MPs on committee were sceptical the government could bank on winning
possible legal actions against suppliers to the development, the most
expensive government-financed building this century.
When the new library was approved by the then Mrs Shirley Williams in 1978
on a site in London's Euston Road, it was costed at Pounds 116m and was
expected to be completed by the mid 1980s.
Poor building controls by the Property Services Agency, privatised in 1992,
and continuous cuts by the Treasury delayed the development until a much
smaller building - adding only an additional 76 readers' seats to the 1,100
in the old reading room in the British Museum - was approved.
Mr Brooke said he hoped that the British Library could take over the site in
1996. There could then be a further delay of up to two years while the stock
of 12m books was brought from almost 20 sites around London.
The latest setbacks to the development involve cabling and the sprinkling
system. Consultants are assessing the extent of the problem, and the
responsibility for malfunctions, and are expected to report in August. The
government will then be better able to give a timetable.
Mr Brooke denied allegations of illegal practices, involving contractors
spinning out the work and repeating installations. He blamed the
drip-feeding of cash in the 1980s for the rising costs.
Since becoming heritage secretary in 1992, Mr Brooke has increased
investment in the project - a move criticised by many in the performing arts
who believe that extra funding contributed to the reduction in the grant for
the Arts Council in 1994-95.
Dr Brian Lang, the British Library chief executive, told the committee that
the library wanted to take over a safe, healthy, efficient building but it
was not being over-scrupulous about the condition of the fixtures and
fittings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
