<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Merger of anti-fraud agencies is proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Serious Fraud Office and the Fraud Investigation Group of the Crown
Prosecution Service should be merged to improve the effectiveness of the
fight against financial crime, an inquiry ordered by Sir Nicholas Lyell QC,
the attorney-general, concluded yesterday.
The report by Mr John Graham, a senior Treasury civil servant, makes no
recommendation about whether the merged body should be controlled by the
prosecution service or be in effect an enlarged fraud office. But it does
propose extending the fraud office's 'Section 2' powers to the police. The
powers, which remove the right to silence and compel witnesses to answer
questions, can be used only by the SFO's lawyers and accountants.
Sir Nicholas gave no indication of the direction of government thinking, and
said yesterday that studies into the possibility of executive agency status
for the fraud office and CPS would have to be completed before any final
decision was taken.
The report identifies a series of shortcomings in the operations of both the
fraud office and the investigation group which have different powers and
approaches to combating fraud. It makes a number of recommendations for
immediate organisational and managerial improvements.
The fraud office's management systems are not exploited fully, while the
investigation group has few useful systems in place, it says. Both
organisations should improve their use of outside barristers while the fraud
office should review its use of police officers brought in on secondment.
The report concludes that the main advantages of a merger would be to
improve resource allocation and the extension of Section 2 powers, which it
said had proved 'an effective investigation tool'.
Although it does not make a final recommendation, the report suggests the
fraud office should be brought under the control of the prosecution service,
provided it can be ring-fenced from the rest of the CPS. However, it
acknowledges that this could be politically damaging.
The report also concludes that both fraud bodies should accept cases
involving Pounds 1m or more. However, the fraud office, which accepts cases
involving at least Pounds 5m, rejected the recommendation, saying that it
does not make sense for both organisations to adopt the same financial
threshold.
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
