<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / CSO publishes first country breakdown of invisible trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK runs large invisible trade deficits with the rest of the European
Union and the European Free Trade Association, but these are offset by big
surpluses elsewhere in the world, according to figures published by the
Central Statistical Office yesterday, Peter Norman writes.
The CSO's first ever country-by-country breakdown of Britain's invisible
trade, covering services, investment income and transfers, showed that in
1992 the UK ran a deficit of Pounds 3.94bn with the rest of the EU and one
of Pounds 3.22bn with the EFTA countries. But surpluses elsewhere produced a
positive balance of Pounds 4.79bn on the global account.
The UK had invisible surpluses of Pounds 4.39bn with Japan, Pounds 2.26bn
with the US and Pounds 1.59bn with Australasia. Inside the EU, the UK ran a
Pounds 4bn surplus with Italy, but deficits of Pounds 1.86bn with the
Netherlands, Pounds 1.26bn with Germany and Pounds 1.18bn with Spain.
Economic Trends No 488, June 1994. HMSO. Pounds 13.25.
</TEXT>
