<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Merseyside faces creditors' action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Merseyside Development Corporation, a government agency, faces legal action
by creditors over the opera concert to celebrate the visit of the Columbus
Grand Regatta tall ships to Liverpool and Birkenhead in 1992.
Only about Pounds 10,000 of assets remain in Carroll Promotions, the failed
company set up with a share capital of Pounds 2 by Mr Brendan Carroll, the
corporation's public relations consultant, to run the concert.
Mr Sandy Jack of Parkin S. Booth, the liquidator, yesterday told creditors
he would not apply for a winding-up order until the Commons public accounts
committee has published its report.
Creditors include the corporation, which had to inject more than Pounds
400,000 to save the concert after poor ticket sales. Smaller creditors say
they believed the event was in effect sponsored and underwritten by the
corporation, which should therefore be held responsible for all the debts.
Mr Nicholas Corke, owner-manager of Freehand Design, who represents himself
and 13 other creditors, said yesterday: 'We believe we have a fair chance of
proving the relationship between the corporation and Carroll Promotions was
that of principal and agent, so the corporation would then be liable to pay
us.'
A contract putting Carroll Promotions at a legal arm's length from the
corporation was signed only days before the concert, when it was already
clear there would be substantial losses.
Mr Corke said a loss of Pounds 187,000 was already projected in a budget
attached to the contract. He said the contract was only supposed to operate
if they event went into profit.
The National Audit Office, the public spending watchdog, said in a critical
report in April that eventual losses would be about Pounds 695,000.
</TEXT>
