<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Fresh job blow at Du Pont hits 720
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Du Pont, the world's largest nylon maker, yesterday announced it was cutting
more than 700 jobs at its British operations. Most of the job losses will be
from former Imperial Chemical Industries facilities which Du Pont acquired
last year, Paul Abrahams writes.
The UK bore the brunt of a previous round of cuts by Du Pont in September
last year when 860 lost their posts and a plant in Pontypool, south Wales,
was closed. Most of the latest job losses will be at Wilton, Teesside, where
520 posts will disappear. An additional 200 jobs will go at Gloucester and
Doncaster.
Du Pont's announcement drew sharp reactions from unions. Mr Fred Higgs,
national secretary of the TGWU general union, which represents most of the
workers due to lose their jobs, said the Teesside closure was 'a cynical
betrayal of more than 500 loyal workers who were promised by Du Pont, only a
year ago, that their jobs were secure'.
Du Pont intends to close a plant at Wilton which manufactures adipic acid, a
raw material for nylon, by early 1997. The company is setting up a joint
venture with Rhone-Poulenc of France to expand an adipic acid facility at
Chalampe, Alsace.
The group also plans to close the Wilton plant manufacturing
hexamethylenediamine, the other main raw material for nylon. The chemical
will be supplied from other Du Pont facilities, primarily in Texas and
Canada. About 160 Du Pont employees will be left at Wilton.
</TEXT>
