<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Beckett puts emphasis on leadership continuity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the interim Labour leader, yesterday presented herself
as the candidate of unity and continuity in Labour's leadership election.
In a personal manifesto, Mrs Beckett set out to challenge the widespread
view among party members that she is the candidate of the left.
She said she believed she could win the leadership, in spite of indications
that she is trailing badly behind Mr Tony Blair, the modernist shadow home
secretary.
Mrs Beckett declined, however, to say whether she was still interested in
the deputy leadership, which she is also contesting, or if she would serve
in the shadow cabinet under Mr Blair or Mr John Prescott, the third
leadership candidate.
Mrs Beckett's eight-page glossy manifesto sets out to capitalise on her
experience as the interim leader and the only former minister in the race.
It pictures her with US President Clinton at the Detroit unemployment summit
earlier this year, in a factory, and visiting a school, recalling her three
years as a junior education minister in the 1970s.
The manifesto offers few insights into the character of a Labour government
led by Mrs Beckett, mainly because of the inability of leadership candidates
to change established party policy.
But it offers strong support to the concept of Labour as 'a very broad
church' and promises to unite the party behind an 'honest, straight-forward,
inclusive style of leadership'.
Launching the manifesto, Mrs Beckett said she knew 'the party and the
movement from the bottom up better than anybody else in the race'.
She urged the party to challenge the 'myth' that there was no alternative to
the Conservatives, who she said were 'stuck in a political and ideological
cul-de-sac'.
Mrs Beckett said Labour must change the political culture of Britain. 'We
must set people free to dream. Then we must build up a programme of how to
begin to deliver that vision,' she said.
Friends of Mrs Beckett said that the release of the manifesto had been timed
to coincide with the despatch of voting papers to the 4.5m members of the
party's electoral college.
It is designed to raise questions about the electoral appeal of the other
candidates, such as the ability of Mr Blair to defend Labour's heartlands,
and whether Mr Prescott can win fresh support in the south of England.
Mr Prescott is expected to deliver his personal manifesto - the last of the
three - early next week. The election result will be declared on July 21.
</TEXT>
