<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Details in place for Bank shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England's biggest internal reorganisation for more than a decade
will come into force on Monday when the Bank's main activities will be
divided into two 'wings' - charged respectively with securing monetary and
financial stability.
The shake-up, in preparation since December, means the departure of nine of
the Bank's top 45 managers and between 10 and 15 of the 150 high-level staff
immediately below head-of-division level. About 80 clerical staff will also
go. But the Bank will recruit more analysts, junior managers and graduates.
The reorganisation has caused considerable distress at the Bank. However, it
said yesterday that there were no compulsory redundancies. Some senior staff
have found jobs elsewhere, others have been offered severance terms, while a
special severance scheme has been opened for clerical staff.
The Bank's four existing executive directors will head the two wings,
forming the top management layer under Mr Eddie George, the governor, and Mr
Rupert Pennant-Rea, his deputy. Five officials have been appointed to a new
rank of deputy director, just below executive director level.
The deputy directors - who must count as the Bank's rising stars - are Mr
Graham Kentfield (chief cashier and banking and market services), Mr John
Townend (market operations), Mr Bill Allen (monetary analysis), Mr Michael
Foot (bank supervision) and Mr Alastair Clark (regulatory policy and
liaison).
</TEXT>
