<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Customers unsure of need for change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, CHRIS TIGHE and NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Heseltine's plans for the Post Office ran into a mixture of cynicism and
fear among shift workers taking a break in Royal Mail Street, Birmingham,
outside one of the biggest sorting offices in Europe.
Among their customers, the large postal users, there was a general welcome
for the proposals - but disagreement over whether privatisation was
necessary.
As the Birmingham postal workers leaned against a wall, passing around a
news agency report on the government's favoured partial privatisation
option, there was little argument. One said: 'I can't see why they want to
sell it off when they're making these profits - Pounds 306m, wasn't it?.'
Another said: 'Everybody believes the public is going to suffer.'
Some argued that greed for profits and shares was the main motivation for
change, and that the postal workers would suffer. One said: 'They're only
out to make a quicker buck and bigger profits for the shareholders. I don't
think it's for the good of the public. To do that, to make the bigger
profits, they've got to cut jobs.'
Some said the Post Office was already cutting postal workers' jobs. There
were more casuals and part-time staff. 'It's going to get worse,' they said.
'They're going to run the post office on a part-time basis.'
There were some who regretted what they saw as the passing of the Post
Office culture. One worker said: 'The Post Office isn't the Post Office I
joined as a lad. Now it's all down to cost. A few years ago they said it was
a job for life. I can't see that going on.'
There was support for the public-sector option. 'If you keep us in the
public sector and give us the right to compete, we'd put a lot of the
competitors out of business.'
Among the large postal users there was more support for the government.
Mr Mark Elwes, director of postal and telecommunications affairs at the
Direct Marketing Association, said there was a clear need for change.
He said: 'The Post Office does need to be freed from political control. If
it is to work properly it must have long-term financial freedom as well as
political freedom. The question is whether it needs to be privatised to
achieve that.'
Mr Leon Morelli, chairman of the Mail Users' Association, said that
ownership was 'in a sense a side issue'.
He said: 'What we want to see is commercial freedom. We don't see why that
can't be given within the public sector.
'We would want to see it very strongly regulated if it were privatised.'
He added that there needed to be 'some permanent legislative link' between a
privatised Royal Mail and a publicly-owned Post Office Counters in order to
safeguard small post offices.
Mr Colin Mitchell, chairman of the European Mail and Express Services Users'
Association, said the most important issue was to remove the
Treasury-imposed external finance limit from the Post Office.
He added: 'That would be very difficult under state ownership because of the
government's attitude. I think the solution has to be one of the other two
options.'
The British Printing Industry Federation said the green paper was 'long
overdue' and that 'anything that gives greater commercial freedom to the
Post Office is to be desired'.
It was anxious, however, that a universal service with uniform prices should
be maintained.
Ms Sally Greengrass, director-general of the charity Age Concern, emphasised
the need to protect local post offices which had a 'social value to old
people and should not be sacrificed for financial targets'.
</TEXT>
