FT  01 JUL 94 / Brent Walker documents 'missing'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountants investigating the finances of Brent Walker received no
supporting documentation for transactions alleged to be responsible for
boosting the property and leisure group's profits, the Old Bailey heard
yesterday.
Mr Michael Oldham, a Touche Ross accountant, told the court that he was one
of a team appointed by the group's bankers in October 1990 to investigate
and report on the financial state of the Brent Walker group.
The team's inquiries were separate from those carried out by the Serious
Fraud Office at about the same time.
Mr Oldham asked for documentation about two Pounds 4.5m payments by Brent
Walker to a Tunisian bank, but was told by Mr George Walker, the group's
former chairman and chief executive, and Mr Wilfred Aquilina, its former
finance director, that these records had gone missing, he said.
The two Pounds 4.5m payments were part of the attempt to conceal the
profit-boosting, it was alleged.
Mr Walker and Mr Aquilina deny charges of theft, false accounting and
conspiring to falsify the accounts of the Brent Walker group.
The prosecution alleges that the two men conspired to inflate the company's
profits by Pounds 19.3m between 1984 and 1987. The trial continues today.
