<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Pensions to top Major's reform programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cabinet yesterday agreed an autumn legislative programme based on the
twin themes of supply-side and welfare state reform as Mr John Major kept
open the options for an early ministerial reshuffle.
The core bills for the Queen's Speech in November will include measures to
equalise the pension age at 65 and reform pensions law, to cut the cost of
unemployment benefit by introducing a job-seekers' allow-ance and to
establish a new Environmental Protection Agency.
But in an apparent victory for the cabinet's 'consolidators', ministers have
deferred plans for an omnibus privatisation bill and early legislation to
pave the way for the introduction of motorway tolls.
Other casualties of the cautious approach being adopted by the prime
minister include measures to liberalise licensing laws and a proposed reform
of local government housing rules. There remains a question mark over a
further criminal justice bill.
In deference to the sceptics on the Tory back benches, Mr Major has also
resisted pressure to introduce a bill to scrap British summertime in favour
of alignment with European partners.
But senior ministers offered a clear hint last night that the cabinet's
leading radicals - Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Michael
Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary - had all but won their battle
for a Post Office privatisation bill. Ministers said that, subject to the
consultation announced in yesterday's green paper, room had been allowed
within the programme for legislation to allow the sale of the Royal Mail.
Among other controversial legislation will be a bill to provide for the
dismantling of regional health authorities and the extension of fund-holding
by GPs. Ministers have decided against committing themselves to a bill to
reform the operations of the Child Support Agency.
But if political controversy over the CSA refuses to die down - the agency
will be the subject of a Labour-inspired Commons debate on Monday - space
can be found later in the legislative programme.
The programme may also have to include a potentially difficult bill to raise
the limits on Britain's contributions to the European Union, a move almost
certain to spark unrest among Tory Euro-sceptics.
Meanwhile, speculation about the timing of the reshuffle intensified last
night after the government broke with normal practice and delayed announcing
the date of the parliamentary recess. Mr Major is expected to reshape the
cabinet within a week or so of the break.
It is understood that the prime minister has all but finalised the details
of what is promised as the biggest government shake-up since the 1992
general election.
Party managers insisted that MPs would continue to meet at least until the
third week of July - but ministers raised the possibility that the summer
break could start in two weeks time. That in turn would allow Mr Major to
bring forward the cabinet changes. Whitehall insiders have pencilled in the
week beginning July 11 as the most likely for the shake-up but have refused
to rule out earlier changes.
</TEXT>
