<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / MPs say promises to forces broken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's forces have been so stretched by their engagement in former
Yugoslavia that promises about conditions of service for soldiers and
sailors have been abandoned, a cross-party committee of MPs said yesterday.
In a report two weeks before the expected announcement of wide-ranging cuts
in defence spending, the Commons defence committee argues that even now the
armed forces are thinly spread.
The committee questioned whether the Treasury was qualified to judge which
forms of defence spending were dispensable and pointedly reminded Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, the defence secretary, of a comment in the April white paper: 'The
possession of such a valuable and prestigious national asset as our armed
services is not a luxury.'
The committee said: 'This is a message which, it seems, is yet to be fully
received by the Treasury.'
The MPs reserved their harshest words for the capacity limits shown up by
the deployment of 2,500 ground troops in central Bosnia and ships in the
Adriatic.
It says guarantees to sailors about the proportion of time they would spend
overseas had been broken as a result of the Adriatic operation.
'It is a shocking comment on the degree to which the Royal Navy's resources
are overstretched that even the Navy's relatively unambitious welfare
targets are being constantly breached,' the committee added.
The government has said next month's defence cuts, designed to shave at
least Pounds 750m from the annual defence budget, will have no effect on the
armed forces' fighting ability because they will focus on trimming the cost
of support services.
Defence Committee Sixth Report. HMSO. Pounds 24.40.
