FT  01 JUL 94 / Turkish paper buys into rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey's Milliyet newspaper took a 35 per cent stake in one of its two main
rivals, Hurriyet, yesterday in a move a Hurriyet executive said was designed
to cut costs. Mr Yasar Eroglu said the sale of half of Hurriyet Holding's 70
per cent share in the daily to Milliyet did not herald a merger, but would
allow the two high-spending papers to share costs. He did not say how much
the Milliyet owner, Mr Aydin Dogan, had paid for the stake in Hurriyet.
Hurriyet's net daily sales are around 508,000 and Milliyet sells about
360,000 copies. Both are locked in circulation wars with the biggest daily
Sabah, which sells about 558,000.
