<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / German constitution changed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's parliament voted yesterday to amend the post-war constitution to
take account of unification, but it turned down other proposed amendments
and was set to reject several more radical changes. The deputies, meeting in
Berlin's historic Reichstag building, voted 622 to three with four
abstentions for stronger commitments to the rights of women and the
handicapped and for a pledge to protect the environment for later
generations. But they rejected clauses on respecting ethnic minorities and
on the division of power between the federal government and the 16 states,
whose powers Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats (CDU) have refused
to extend. The CDU has pledged to block the more radical motions, including
one from the combined opposition parties to recognise common law
relationships, whether heterosexual or homosexual. Since changes require a
two-thirds majority, it was almost certain that only the reforms which had
cross-party consensus would pass.
</TEXT>
