<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUL 94 / Airbus airliner crashes on test
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Seven Airbus crew members including the European consortium chief test
pilot, Mr Nick Warner, were killed yesterday when a new Airbus A330
wide-bodied jet crashed during tests at Toulouse airport. The twin-engine
350-seat airliner went down shortly after take-off while the crew were
testing the auto-pilot system after a simulated engine failure. The test was
being conducted in extreme conditions with the aircraft on a steep angle of
climb and flying at very low speed. It is the first time an A330 has
crashed. There are six in airline service, with Air Inter, the French
domestic carrier, and Aer Lingus, the Irish flag carrier. All are powered by
General Electric engines. The crashed airliner had Pratt and Whitney
engines. Airbus said last night the two black box flight recorders had been
found. Two Britons were among the crew members killed yesterday. Three
Frenchmen and two Italians also died. The A330 first went into airline
service last year and Airbus has so far won total orders for 118.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
