FT  01 JUL 94 / Serbs repossess heavy arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SARAJEVO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Serbs have pulled heavy weapons out of United Nations-monitored storage in
Croatia and moved some tanks into neighbouring Bosnia, a UN official said
yesterday. The report fed fears of an escalation in fighting as
international mediators began trying to 'sell' the warring parties in Bosnia
a new peace. Serbs took almost 20 tanks and artillery pieces from storage
over the past several days, said UN spokesman Mr Paul Risley. Some were
moved across the border into the Bihac area of northwestern Bosnia, where a
rebel Moslem leader's troops are fighting government loyalists. 'We are
concerned there by the presence of several tanks and heavy weapons belonging
to the military of the Serb authorities in Knin, which have recently been
deployed across the border,' he said. Knin is the self-styled capital of
regions captured by Serbs and held since a six-month war in 1991. They
refuse to submit to Croatian authority and hope to unite their regions with
Serb-held parts of Bosnia and Serbia proper.
